adian Law -- tThinking It Was Love: Adolescent Dating Violence -- tWhose Failure to Protect? Child Welfare Interventions When Men Abuse Mothers -- t“Change your number”: When Technology Intersects with Coercive Control, Intimate Partner Violence, and Legal Systems -- tIdentifying, Assessing, and Counselling Male Intimate Partner Violence Perpetrators and Abused Women -- tThe Sombre Side of Care: The Abuse and Neglect of Older People in Canada -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPicture family life in Canada. Does it include women or girls being murdered, on average, every two and a half days? Or the fact that intimate partner violence counts as nearly one-third of all reports to police? Or that child or elder abuse is more common than you might imagine? Written for students, instructors, practitioners, and advocates in all related fields, this expanded and updated third edition of Cruel But Not Unusual: Violence in Families in Canada offers the latest research, thinking, and strategies to address this hard reality in Canada today. Violence takes many forms inside relationships and families, and the systems charged with responding and helping can actually add to the harm, further isolating and endangering victims. Nowhere is this more evident than in intentionally marginalized communities, such as Indigenous, Black, people of colour, LGBTQI2S+, people with disabilities, and immigrant, refugee, and non-status women. From recommendations on resisting anti-Black state-sanctioned violence, to a call to action on partner abuse within LGBTQI2S+ communities, the book offers bold ideas for moving forward, highlighting the work of researchers and activists from these communities. Using a range of perspectives (feminist, trauma-informed, intersectional, anti-oppression) and including diverse couple and family relationships and settings (foster care, group homes, institutions), the contributors track violence across the life course, addressing the impact on the brain, trauma, coercive control, resilience, disclosing abuse, the MeToo movement, self-care, and providing practical case examples and guidelines for working with children, youth, adults, couples, families, and groups. The result is an authoritative source that offers new insights and approaches to inform understanding, policy, practice, and prevention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbused older peoplezCanada. 0aChildren and violencezCanada. 0aFamily violencezCanada. 0aWomenxViolence againstzCanada. 4aFamily & Relationships: Child Abuse. 4aFamily & Relationships: Domestic Violence. 4aLaw: Child Advocacy. 4aSocial Science: Gender Studies. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Abuse / Domestic Partner Abuse.2bisacsh  aBlack families.  aIndigenous.  aIntimate partner violence.  aLGBTQI2S+/Queer Communities.  achild abuse and neglect.  achild maltreatment effects.  acoercive control.  adisabilities.  adomestic violence.  aelder abuse.  aexposure to violence.  afamily violence.  amental health.  anewcomer/immigrant/refugees.  arecovery.  aresilience.  asexual violence.  astructural violence.  atechnology.  atrauma.1 aAlaggia, Ramona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlaggia, Ramona, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAyoub, Mariam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaskin, Cyndy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhuyan, Rupaleem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollin-Vézina, Delphine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Shaindl L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab